• Welcome to our LOCKDOWN OFFICE •

Since the start of the pandemic and lockdown in South Africa, I have been making daily updates about our "Lockdown Office" to send to Pieter's boss. 
.
Part of me hopes that these daily updates will encourage his boss to allow him to work from home more often when this pandemic is over. The updates are my way of making everyone feel that they are still at the office and not missing eachother. 
.
I thought that since we are now on day 106 of these updates, I could upload them here to keep as memories of this time our family went through and so that I can look back on them. 
.
You are welcome to follow along on our daily Home Hub Updates and luckily for you, there are already 106 to catch up on so you can binge. üòâ
.
We started self-isolating a couple of days before the official lockdown started in South Africa. 
.

.

- Pieter received the "worker of the day award" for being most productive. 
- We will be talking to the slackers about the dishes that aren't done.

- Pieter also sent a complaint to HR about his crying co-worker. 
- We have issued a warning to the co-worker that she needs to work on her attitude. (Nina's sleeping now)
- Pieter also had to wipe a co-worker's butt. 
- We are going to have to remind Pieter when to change into his "work PJ's" and back to his "home PJ's" ü§£

Nine Muslim women from Melapalayam had deliveries lined up in April. This reporter accessed audio recordings where relatives of some of these women plead with the doctors, only to be told they can't be admitted over explicit instructions from the district administration. The district administration denies having given any such orders. 
.
.
.
These women travelled to their usual hospitals, where they were turned away. With no option left, they finally approached Tirunelveli Medical College Hospital (TMCH), a government facility at Highground.
.
.
.
Rizwana, 21, from North Thaika Street in Melapalayam, was reluctant to get herself admitted at TMCH Highground owing to previous bad experiences. “Nobody cares about you there. The place is also not very well kept and this was my first pregnancy,” she explained. 
.
.
.
However, she was left with no choice. “As soon as I told them I am from Melapalayam, I could sense everybody just freeze. I stood outside the Labour Ward as much as I could, as I didn’t want to antagonise anybody,” says Rizwana. 
.
.
.
Nasreen Fathima was denied admission at Annai Velankanni Hospital, and witnessed Rizwana's plight. 
.
.
.
“I saw Rizwana struggle with her urine drip by herself. Some nurses were good but most of them weren’t. They spoke to all of us very harshly and kept yelling at us,” says Nasreen. “The room was dirty, there were constant long power cuts, the fans weren’t working and the bathroom didn’t even have a light. And there was nobody to attend to us,” she adds.
.
.
.
Following the trauma for expecting mothers, Crescent Hospital in the area was approached by leaders including Nasreen's father as a temporary solution. 
.
.
.
Read the full report by Greeshma Kuthar at Firstpost.com
.
.
.

node.text:
Tamil Nadu Lockdown Diary  Covid 19 outbreak, prejudice and denial of healthcare to Muslims 
.
.
.
Peer Muhammad, a liver cancer patient and resident of Melapalayam, a Muslim neighbourhood in Tirunelveli was a tragic casualty of prejudicial mismanagement in Tamil Nadu. 
.
.
.
He initially travelled to Regional Cancer Centre (RCC), Thiruvananthapuram for treatment until the lockdown. The RCC then directed him to the nearest government facility for chemotherapy. 
.
.
.
His first visit to the facility was on 30 March, a day after Melapalayam was shut down. According to son Muhammad Ibrahim, they weren't allowed inside after half a day's wait in the scorching heat. They re-attempted on 22 April when Muhammad’s condition further deteriorated, still in vain. Swipe left for the receipts. 
.
.
.
A video of Peer Muhammad shot on the same day shows him in an extremely precarious condition. Five days later, he died.
.
.
.
From an entire area being cordoned off as part of 'COVID 19 protocol', to pregnant women and grievously sick patients in the locality being denied treatment, the healthcare prejudice and stigma are both real and dangerous. Melapalayam was branded as a 'corona hub', in spite of just 32 cases in an area with 3 lakh people. The same is also in direct contradiction to the World Health Organisation's order to desist from further alienating victims of the virus.
.
.
.
The area was completely shut down on the orders of the District Collector Shilpa Prakash Satish. The DC also ordered a stop to all vehicular movement and barricaded the locality completely. The seemingly misplaced management resulted in severe distress for those in need of medical attention. 
.
.
.
Arabi Gnaniyar, an ambulance driver (swipe left for photo) who saw patients from Melapayalam struggling with accessing medical care, said, “Everybody thinks Melapalayam is where coronavirus is spreading from. I’ve travelled across Tirunelveli and the adjoining villages. People are speaking as if COVID-19 originated from Melapalayam, not China.” 
.
.
.

Rise above it all üèî
‚†Ä
Without valleys, there are no peaks. Without lows, there are no highs. Such is life. You cannot truly appreciate the good, without enduring the bad. So, I must remind myself.
‚†Ä
Just when I felt I was getting into a rhythm with my surfing and starting to skate and practice yoga again, I just had to go fall over a barrier and twist my ankle ü§¶üèΩ‍‚ôÄÔ∏è Could’ve been so much worse and if a sprain is one of the heaviest things I have on my plate, I realize my plate’s not even loaded that full at the moment. That said, it still feels like some freedom has been stripped away as I’m making myself pull back and take it easy while my body can heal. Physical activity has been my biggest outlet for keeping myself sane and pushing myself out of a negative headspace. (Also, am I lame for wishing I was doing some gnarly skate trick instead of wiping out from mere walking?!?! Lol)
‚†Ä
This year has been particularly tumultuous for everyone. For me, I’ve had some really fun times visiting back home, Nicaragua, and Miami, and then playing around with many types of skateboards. I’ve also felt down and hopeless with all that’s going on in the world and had days where all I wanted to do was lie on the sofa, binge Netflix, and indulge in comfort foods. I just started coming out of that a few weeks ago as the beaches began to reopen here and I feel lucky that this ankle thing happened now and not then, because I’m just so much more equipped to deal with it. Now, time not spent surfing and skating seems to have me pivoting harder towards reading, playing around with my photos, and tinkering around more in the kitchen. It’s not a total wash… but damn, I can’t wait to get back out there.
‚†Ä
So, that’s what’s been going on with me. How have you been, friends?
.
.
.
.

I hate throwing out food that hasn't been touched.

So I had to come up with something to make with some overripe bananas in the fruit bowl.

This is a Chocolate Banana cake.

The recipe calls for choc chips but I improvised by chopping up a Top Deck slab and sprinkled some icing sugar on top.

I also substituted the applesauce as an ingredient with pureed canned pears. 

Delicious in taste and can last up to a week by refrigerating.

You can also heat up leftovers and top with ice cream or custard.

The lockdown made me more ardent to write the content thriving in my mind.  Writing helps me reduce stress and has become a easy platform to express my notions. By writing, I have become the coauthor of many anthologies. 
 Writting is a passion which is yet to be heighten and there's always an accomodation for learning.  Every person has his own story to express but difference is made by those who find way out to explain amd express the world.

Gunjan Jain is a textile designer, researcher and founder of Vriksh, design studio. She has been working with handloom weavers for the past 12 years in India. For Gunjan, Vriksh has been a discovery of herself, her art and the weaves of Odisha. 

Vriksh’s new collection “Bali Jatra” (2nd and 3rd images)was launched early this year. 

“The Covid-19 pandemic and lockdown has severely affected the handloom sector, which was already reeling under the impact of demonetisation and GST. For centuries, the handloom weaver has continued to work from home, offering the world the choice of a conscious living, which is sustainable, local and green. These weavers offer me the hope and the conviction to carry on my journey in the handmade sector”.

This beautiful piece is written for The Punch Magazine Art Issue, curated by curator-author and our contributing editor Ina Puri.
